    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm struggling with some of the concepts for my undergrad physics midterm. can u explain quantum entanglement in simple terms? like, what's the main difference between that and just regular classical correlation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fascinating, concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine two of these linked particles, and they are separated by a vast distance—even across the galaxy. When you measure a property of one particle, like its spin, you instantly know the corresponding property of the other particle.\n\nThe main difference from classical correlation, like having two matching gloves in separate boxes, is that in entanglement, the properties *don't* have a definite state until the moment of measurement. In the classical case, the gloves *were* left and right before you opened the box; the correlation is pre-determined, not instantaneously decided upon measurement. This \"spooky action at a distance,\" as Einstein called it, is what makes it so weird.",
